Find $-(-(-5))(-3)+11$.
}

\textbf{Answer:} Each negative sign in $-(-(-5))$ means to take the negation, so in $-(-(-5))$ we take the negation three times. Taking the negation once, we get $-5$. Taking the negation a second time, we get $-(-5)=5$. Finally, taking the negation a third time, we get $-5$ and $-(-(-5)))=-5$. So we get$$-(-(-5)))(-3)+11=(-5)(-3)+11.$$Recalling that a negative number times a negative number gives a positive number, we get$$(-5)(-3)+11=15+11=\boxed{26}.$$
